comment_text: Space travel is non-existent.   WAKE UP YOU ZOMBIES!!!!!!  So many flaws in so called space travel if zero gravity how does an engines thrusters push against non-existent matter to propel it forwards.  Why do astronauts always appear to be 'bouncing' constantly push up with their legs yet repeatedly come back down bit like they are in a harness with cgi trickery or green screens at play oooh don't say that as the Zombies will 'try' and ridicule you.  Never in history has a camera been focussed from a rocket from start (Earth) to finish (space) NEVER NEVER NEVER wonder why this is.....  They tell us and have been drip feeding us lies since the sixties about space travel yet why has no everyday normal man/woman been to space or allowed? Plane travel became readily available within years of being invented yet so called space travel that has been supposedly been going on for 50+years is not readily available yet....why is this? Yea sure you can buy tickets from spacex or Richard Branson to experience 0 gravity for a short space of time but that is not space travel that is just a short burst of a zero gravity experience that can be achieved by angles and speed. If you fly any plane in the right way at the right speed, you can go weightless. By effectively throwing the aircraft into orbit within the Earth's atmosphere, you can enter the world of the parabolic flight and experience Zero-G, exactly like in space. Oooh and no one that has supposedly bought these tickets has actually gone up yet either...tic tok tic tok the lies keep coming

author: Cain Able
comment_text: So it's evidentially a metaphor for being trapped with car purchases. All the other floors, despite how they typically portray them as unenviable situations, they are all progressive in their actions. Unnecessary evils if you will.   The car however, is on the top floor of a starkly contrasted room, with absolutely no possibility of driving it, just the signifier, that instead of being outdoors and enjoying life, you are only observing it through a glass window.   Key lesson in life? You probably don't need a new car.

author: 2012Hem
comment_text: This is false advertising, my experience at Jaipur Roshan Motors Hyundai service was horrible. Not a single person in the service centre was happy to get his car serviced with them. Hyundai car owner who comes for service is not a customer for them, they treat him like a lamp to be butchered. I met with a very minor accident and send my car for repair since it was closer to my home. They claimed my engine was seized and demanded 1.5 lakhs as an estimated cost since I knew they wanted to rob me I asked them to return my car, they bluntly refused to return the car and said they have started repairing it and I need to pay them 60000 INR if I want to take away my car unrepaired. I asked them to show the car otherwise I told them I will complain to the police. They agreed to show me the car and to my utter surprise, they had not even touched the car for repairing and they were just lying about that the repair of the car was in process.  When I confronted Hyundai Service person he disappeared from the scene. My advice don't trust Hyundai company service centres, take a bit of independent advice from outside, one of my close friend who used to work with Hyundai dealership told me the car dealers don't make much money by selling cars, they make 90% of the profit by serving cars. Be safe and don't get robbed in the daylight.

author: Kajal Sinha
comment_text: "I am a military doctor and I have a hyundai i10, due to my work I have to travel a lot. Few months back my i10 met with an accident. I sent my driver to hyundai service centre for Repair. As our CAMP had very poor network I could not had a word with my driver. When I came back to my resident at 8pm, my driver told me that the Repair would take 15-20 day. I was tensed as i needed the car after 2 day for I had to go meet my family. My leaves were already approved and could not be postponed. So I told my driver to get it back and I will Repair later. Arround 7 am on my way to CAMP I called the service centre, just to try if I could speak to some one as after that i will not have network in my camp. I was not sure as this was too early for any one to be at office. But opposite to my expectations someone picked my call. Thankgod. And I explained him my situation and told him to cancel the repair. He told me that Repair could not be cancelled as it's already started. Could not speak further as network had gone off. I was tensed for the whole day. For I had already sent my driver, official vehicle were not allowed during vacation, and no other way to meet my parents , whom I get to meet only once in a year. That day I stayed in CAMP till 10 pm then went to my Residency to my surprise I saw a Grand i10 parked outside my house. My driver told me that Repair could not be cancelled but service centre had provided replacement car till my i10 is repaired. I cannot express my happiness as all problems were solved. And how thoughtful they are. I just remember next day CALLING that person to thank and he said ""koi nahi sir aap hamare liye intna sochte ho toh hamara bhi kuch farz banta hai. Koi bhi problem ho sidha mujhai call kjhiea"" Really respect for hyundai. Although I am now transferred to other state I remember them and Now I have exchanged my i10 with Verna suggested by him, even better. Regards Major K P Sinha."

author: pranshu gupta
comment_text: I got the car repaired under insurance. All fine. (VIN: MALCU41ULDM108334).   Then I got a call that car has no fuel from the service technician Yogender (9958211553). I said, ok, get 1-2 liters done. Now, I went to collect my car and was told that Rs. 500 worth of diesel has been bought from market in a can and filled in my car. When I enquired why 500 ( more than 9 liters), I was told that diesel car cant start in 1-2 liters of fuel and we took a call of 500 rs. I trusted and I was fine. I paid and when i went to collect the car. I realised that the car is in 'reserve sign'. There is limited fuel in the car and as per indicator not worth 9 liters.  So I called back the technician, who assured me that 500 rs was spent for fuel.  Since the car has a 43 liter fuel capacity and a reserve mark of 5-6 liters I was not convinced and called for the duty manager. The manager told me, we can take a can and a pipe, suck out diesel and thats it! When i objected to the vague explanatnation, I was told, it will take 4 hours, we will take out fuel tank and assure you. And everything was happening in a tone of mocking me for pointing out that there has been some misdeed.  I argued endlessly but what can a poor bloody customer with just one car do to a company which sells thousands in a month! So i came back with my teeth clenched and decided to write this email.  They showed me receipt of 500 rs for diesel bought, which has no validity since it does not have the car number and any such receipt can be procured from a pump (especially since the fuel station is next door to the service station).   I am not sure what your policies are, since you anyways sell so many cars and your dealers have the 'right' to loot the customers.   I have been looted and I need an answer!

comment_text: "We bought a 2nd hand kia (same as hyundai) back in 2006, it was 2 years old... A foreign family wanted to trade it for a bigger car and we just got it for someone in our family that just got the license and needed a first car to learn, it was crazy cheap... It had extremely low mileage and was in perfect shape... We've had some other cars during the same time, but the only one what keeps looking as good as then is the kia, the only one that hasn't needed anything else than oil changes and tyres, has been the kia...It just drinks 5 liters of diesel per 100km, 125hp, air conditioning, power steering, power windows... not the fastest car ever but more than some of the extremely appreciated TDI's here... I know its not the same af the video, of course, but comparing cars at ""the same level"", this are extremely underrated cars for just no reason...Today, people buys a brand for what it ""means"", for the ""status"" it gives, just to show what they can buy... Not for what they really want in a car."

author: Kane K
comment_text: "just purchased a 2016 Hyundai i30 here in Australia. Our models come with more standard kit than the model you reviewed here. mine has parking sensors, reverse camera, touch screen multimedia centre, cruise control, and apple car play. only downside is there is no CD player. car is amazing, drives well; build quality is excellent. all this is standard on the ""active"" version (base model).  Australia is the ""biggest market"" for the i30 globally.   I looked at several other cars including the VW polo (great car, too small for me as I am 6ft 3). Toyota corolla (looked boring) and ford fiesta (too expensive). it was either the i30 or a Kia Cerato; as soon as I threatened to look at the Cerato, they matched the drive away price on the cerato for the i30. I am extremely happy with my choice, as the engine has a decent power output compared to the corolla or the polo. another big factor was the 5 year/unlimited km warranty.Â  No wonder Holden and ford struggle to sell the Cruze and fiesta respectively."

author: Doug N
comment_text: I bought this car back in 2013 and drove it 3 years and 80K miles. I had zero problems with it. I foolishly put new tires on the car a month before trading it and had the alignment checked. It was still in perfect alignment. Never had a car stay that true after all those miles. btw...I traded it in on a 2016 Elantra SE sedan. I must say the two cars, although same drive train, are different on the road. The GT definately had a sportier crisper feel whereas the sedan is softer and cushier over all. The sedan also is quiter and gets a tad better mpg. I miss the hatchback practicality of the GT but I like the looks of the sedan better. The GT was my first Hyundai and I must admit I'm sold. A Hyundai enthusiast.

author: John Benton
comment_text: I had a Hyundai I30 for three years, and I've just replaced it with a Hyundai IX20 because I needed more space. With the IX20 the 3-speed auto box soaks up lots of power and changes at too high a speed, so throttle response is almost non-existent. Economy is poor too, but otherwise the IX20 does all that's asked of it. (I just came back from 2 weeks' holiday,in a place about 180 miles of motorway from home. The car cruised at well above the speed limit (70 mph) and returned about 50 mpg. My previous car, an I30 diesel auto was just as fast, a bit quicker and did over 70 mpg, but it was a much smaller car. Will I have another Hyundai? You can bet on it!

comment_text: I have one for a year (august 28). The car is roomy even in the backseat (I'm 1.80 m) with good legroom (more than ford focus, toyota corolla ascent, mazda 3 neo), mine is the 1.6 gas and have enoughÂ power for a city car. Have electric folding mirrors, motorized tilting headlight (Almost standard on Europe, but not here in PanamÃ¡) wich you need to manually tilt in case you feel they're not bright enough, the front seats are very confortable, There are not cup holders in the back, but the center seat is more confortable than the ones with cup holders, I don't really know any problem with the AC, here in Panama is very hot, and the AC performs really good. The front pillar are thick and it may reduce visibility, thatÂ´s true. I bought the i30 over the focus because of the interior design that is simply far better than the focus, The fuel economy ir great. The exterior is really beautiful, a more complex design that turn heads. The handling is soft and the car is very quite. this is more like the elantra hatckback. May be you like the design may be not. May be you donÂ´t like Korean cars, but honestly, this car is amaizing for the tag price and I highly recomend the i30.

comment_text: Space travel is non-existent.   WAKE UP YOU ZOMBIES!!!!!!  So many flaws in so called space travel if zero gravity how does an engines thrusters push against non-existent matter to propel it forwards.  Why do astronauts always appear to be 'bouncing' constantly push up with their legs yet repeatedly come back down bit like they are in a harness with cgi trickery or green screens at play oooh don't say that as the Zombies will 'try' and ridicule you.  Never in history has a camera been focussed from a rocket from start (Earth) to finish (space) NEVER NEVER NEVER wonder why this is.....  They tell us and have been drip feeding us lies since the sixties about space travel yet why has no everyday normal man/woman been to space or allowed? Plane travel became readily available within years of being invented yet so called space travel that has been supposedly been going on for 50+years is not readily available yet....why is this? Yea sure you can buy tickets from spacex or Richard Branson to experience 0 gravity for a short space of time but that is not space travel that is just a short burst of a zero gravity experience that can be achieved by angles and speed. If you fly any plane in the right way at the right speed, you can go weightless. By effectively throwing the aircraft into orbit within the Earth's atmosphere, you can enter the world of the parabolic flight and experience Zero-G, exactly like in space. Oooh and no one that has supposedly bought these tickets has actually gone up yet either...tic tok tic tok the lies keep coming

author: Cain Able
comment_text: So it's evidentially a metaphor for being trapped with car purchases. All the other floors, despite how they typically portray them as unenviable situations, they are all progressive in their actions. Unnecessary evils if you will.   The car however, is on the top floor of a starkly contrasted room, with absolutely no possibility of driving it, just the signifier, that instead of being outdoors and enjoying life, you are only observing it through a glass window.   Key lesson in life? You probably don't need a new car.

author: 2012Hem
comment_text: This is false advertising, my experience at Jaipur Roshan Motors Hyundai service was horrible. Not a single person in the service centre was happy to get his car serviced with them. Hyundai car owner who comes for service is not a customer for them, they treat him like a lamp to be butchered. I met with a very minor accident and send my car for repair since it was closer to my home. They claimed my engine was seized and demanded 1.5 lakhs as an estimated cost since I knew they wanted to rob me I asked them to return my car, they bluntly refused to return the car and said they have started repairing it and I need to pay them 60000 INR if I want to take away my car unrepaired. I asked them to show the car otherwise I told them I will complain to the police. They agreed to show me the car and to my utter surprise, they had not even touched the car for repairing and they were just lying about that the repair of the car was in process.  When I confronted Hyundai Service person he disappeared from the scene. My advice don't trust Hyundai company service centres, take a bit of independent advice from outside, one of my close friend who used to work with Hyundai dealership told me the car dealers don't make much money by selling cars, they make 90% of the profit by serving cars. Be safe and don't get robbed in the daylight.

author: Kajal Sinha
comment_text: "I am a military doctor and I have a hyundai i10, due to my work I have to travel a lot. Few months back my i10 met with an accident. I sent my driver to hyundai service centre for Repair. As our CAMP had very poor network I could not had a word with my driver. When I came back to my resident at 8pm, my driver told me that the Repair would take 15-20 day. I was tensed as i needed the car after 2 day for I had to go meet my family. My leaves were already approved and could not be postponed. So I told my driver to get it back and I will Repair later. Arround 7 am on my way to CAMP I called the service centre, just to try if I could speak to some one as after that i will not have network in my camp. I was not sure as this was too early for any one to be at office. But opposite to my expectations someone picked my call. Thankgod. And I explained him my situation and told him to cancel the repair. He told me that Repair could not be cancelled as it's already started. Could not speak further as network had gone off. I was tensed for the whole day. For I had already sent my driver, official vehicle were not allowed during vacation, and no other way to meet my parents , whom I get to meet only once in a year. That day I stayed in CAMP till 10 pm then went to my Residency to my surprise I saw a Grand i10 parked outside my house. My driver told me that Repair could not be cancelled but service centre had provided replacement car till my i10 is repaired. I cannot express my happiness as all problems were solved. And how thoughtful they are. I just remember next day CALLING that person to thank and he said ""koi nahi sir aap hamare liye intna sochte ho toh hamara bhi kuch farz banta hai. Koi bhi problem ho sidha mujhai call kjhiea"" Really respect for hyundai. Although I am now transferred to other state I remember them and Now I have exchanged my i10 with Verna suggested by him, even better. Regards Major K P Sinha."

author: pranshu gupta
comment_text: I got the car repaired under insurance. All fine. (VIN: MALCU41ULDM108334).   Then I got a call that car has no fuel from the service technician Yogender (9958211553). I said, ok, get 1-2 liters done. Now, I went to collect my car and was told that Rs. 500 worth of diesel has been bought from market in a can and filled in my car. When I enquired why 500 ( more than 9 liters), I was told that diesel car cant start in 1-2 liters of fuel and we took a call of 500 rs. I trusted and I was fine. I paid and when i went to collect the car. I realised that the car is in 'reserve sign'. There is limited fuel in the car and as per indicator not worth 9 liters.  So I called back the technician, who assured me that 500 rs was spent for fuel.  Since the car has a 43 liter fuel capacity and a reserve mark of 5-6 liters I was not convinced and called for the duty manager. The manager told me, we can take a can and a pipe, suck out diesel and thats it! When i objected to the vague explanatnation, I was told, it will take 4 hours, we will take out fuel tank and assure you. And everything was happening in a tone of mocking me for pointing out that there has been some misdeed.  I argued endlessly but what can a poor bloody customer with just one car do to a company which sells thousands in a month! So i came back with my teeth clenched and decided to write this email.  They showed me receipt of 500 rs for diesel bought, which has no validity since it does not have the car number and any such receipt can be procured from a pump (especially since the fuel station is next door to the service station).   I am not sure what your policies are, since you anyways sell so many cars and your dealers have the 'right' to loot the customers.   I have been looted and I need an answer!

comment_text: "We bought a 2nd hand kia (same as hyundai) back in 2006, it was 2 years old... It had extremely low mileage and was in perfect shape... We've had some other cars during the same time, but the only one what keeps looking as good as then is the kia, the only one that hasn't needed anything else than oil changes and tyres, has been the kia...It just drinks 5 liters of diesel per 100km, 125hp, air conditioning, power steering, power windows... not the fastest car ever but more than some of the extremely appreciated TDI's here... I know its not the same af the video, of course, but comparing cars at ""the same level"", this are extremely underrated cars for just no reason...Today, people buys a brand for what it ""means"", for the ""status"" it gives, just to show what they can buy... author: Kane K
comment_text: "just purchased a 2016 Hyundai i30 here in Australia. Our models come with more standard kit than the model you reviewed here. mine has parking sensors, reverse camera, touch screen multimedia centre, cruise control, and apple car play. only downside is there is no CD player. car is amazing, drives well; build quality is excellent. all this is standard on the ""active"" version (base model).  Australia is the ""biggest market"" for the i30 globally.   I looked at several other cars including the VW polo (great car, too small for me as I am 6ft 3). Toyota corolla (looked boring) and ford fiesta (too expensive). it was either the i30 or a Kia Cerato; as soon as I threatened to look at the Cerato, they matched the drive away price on the cerato for the i30. I am extremely happy with my choice, as the engine has a decent power output compared to the corolla or the polo. another big factor was the 5 year/unlimited km warranty.Â  No wonder Holden and ford struggle to sell the Cruze and fiesta respectively."

author: Doug N
comment_text: I bought this car back in 2013 and drove it 3 years and 80K miles. I had zero problems with it. I foolishly put new tires on the car a month before trading it and had the alignment checked. It was still in perfect alignment. Never had a car stay that true after all those miles. btw...I traded it in on a 2016 Elantra SE sedan. I must say the two cars, although same drive train, are different on the road. The GT definately had a sportier crisper feel whereas the sedan is softer and cushier over all. The sedan also is quiter and gets a tad better mpg. I miss the hatchback practicality of the GT but I like the looks of the sedan better. The GT was my first Hyundai and I must admit I'm sold. A Hyundai enthusiast.

author: John Benton
comment_text: I had a Hyundai I30 for three years, and I've just replaced it with a Hyundai IX20 because I needed more space. With the IX20 the 3-speed auto box soaks up lots of power and changes at too high a speed, so throttle response is almost non-existent. Economy is poor too, but otherwise the IX20 does all that's asked of it. (I just came back from 2 weeks' holiday,in a place about 180 miles of motorway from home. The car cruised at well above the speed limit (70 mph) and returned about 50 mpg. My previous car, an I30 diesel auto was just as fast, a bit quicker and did over 70 mpg, but it was a much smaller car. Will I have another Hyundai? You can bet on it!

author: Hector Rivera
comment_text: I have one for a year (august 28). The car is roomy even in the backseat (I'm 1.80 m) with good legroom (more than ford focus, toyota corolla ascent, mazda 3 neo), mine is the 1.6 gas and have enoughÂ power for a city car. Have electric folding mirrors, motorized tilting headlight (Almost standard on Europe, but not here in PanamÃ¡) wich you need to manually tilt in case you feel they're not bright enough, the front seats are very confortable, There are not cup holders in the back, but the center seat is more confortable than the ones with cup holders, I don't really know any problem with the AC, here in Panama is very hot, and the AC performs really good. The front pillar are thick and it may reduce visibility, thatÂ´s true. I bought the i30 over the focus because of the interior design that is simply far better than the focus, The fuel economy ir great. The exterior is really beautiful, a more complex design that turn heads. The handling is soft and the car is very quite. this is more like the elantra hatckback. May be you like the design may be not. May be you donÂ´t like Korean cars, but honestly, this car is amaizing for the tag price and I highly recomend the i30.

comment_text: You'll be surprised all right! I bought a top-of-the-range Santa Fe. Could not have spent more on a Hyundai. Also bought extras and the service plan, so confident was I in Hyundai. author: letsseeif
comment_text: Badge snobs are invariably inadequate 'wankers' compensating for issues such as their small chaps' thingees and/or too much money, or both, and too much spare time. They won't 'get over it' because of factors better left to a psychologist or psychiatrist. However, I still think one should attempt to get over it. It's called 'self help'. The Koreans are here to stay and probably dominate which lobs the snobs of Britannia with a crisis of conscience in that contrary to what the tester chapee in the video says, the car cannot be superior to the sum of its parts. It's a fact that anyone who's done Newtonian Physics will acknowledge this fact in a heartbeat. As for the i30N, it 'ticks all the boxes' and Hy/Kia is clearly on a superior trajectory to Euro cars. I don't expect said 'tester on video' to agree as his job is drum up business and sell cars, and sales of Euro cars pay better, as well as the racial thing, that the sons of Nippon disproved long ago, that Asian cars trump Euros every time where it counts. By the way I'm Anglo Saxon, so no axe to grind there. ps. Does anyone actually design, make and sell British Designed cars in the UK & overseas, any more, and why or why not?

comment_text: So it's evidentially a metaphor for being trapped with car purchases. All the other floors, despite how they typically portray them as unenviable situations, they are all progressive in their actions. Unnecessary evils if you will.   The car however, is on the top floor of a starkly contrasted room, with absolutely no possibility of driving it, just the signifier, that instead of being outdoors and enjoying life, you are only observing it through a glass window.   Key lesson in life? You probably don't need a new car.

author: 2012Hem
comment_text: This is false advertising, my experience at Jaipur Roshan Motors Hyundai service was horrible. Not a single person in the service centre was happy to get his car serviced with them. Hyundai car owner who comes for service is not a customer for them, they treat him like a lamp to be butchered. I met with a very minor accident and send my car for repair since it was closer to my home. They claimed my engine was seized and demanded 1.5 lakhs as an estimated cost since I knew they wanted to rob me I asked them to return my car, they bluntly refused to return the car and said they have started repairing it and I need to pay them 60000 INR if I want to take away my car unrepaired. I asked them to show the car otherwise I told them I will complain to the police. They agreed to show me the car and to my utter surprise, they had not even touched the car for repairing and they were just lying about that the repair of the car was in process.  When I confronted Hyundai Service person he disappeared from the scene. My advice don't trust Hyundai company service centres, take a bit of independent advice from outside, one of my close friend who used to work with Hyundai dealership told me the car dealers don't make much money by selling cars, they make 90% of the profit by serving cars. Be safe and don't get robbed in the daylight.

author: Kajal Sinha
comment_text: "I am a military doctor and I have a hyundai i10, due to my work I have to travel a lot. Few months back my i10 met with an accident. I sent my driver to hyundai service centre for Repair. As our CAMP had very poor network I could not had a word with my driver. When I came back to my resident at 8pm, my driver told me that the Repair would take 15-20 day. I was tensed as i needed the car after 2 day for I had to go meet my family. My leaves were already approved and could not be postponed. So I told my driver to get it back and I will Repair later. Arround 7 am on my way to CAMP I called the service centre, just to try if I could speak to some one as after that i will not have network in my camp. I was not sure as this was too early for any one to be at office. But opposite to my expectations someone picked my call. Thankgod. And I explained him my situation and told him to cancel the repair. He told me that Repair could not be cancelled as it's already started. Could not speak further as network had gone off. I was tensed for the whole day. For I had already sent my driver, official vehicle were not allowed during vacation, and no other way to meet my parents , whom I get to meet only once in a year. That day I stayed in CAMP till 10 pm then went to my Residency to my surprise I saw a Grand i10 parked outside my house. My driver told me that Repair could not be cancelled but service centre had provided replacement car till my i10 is repaired. I cannot express my happiness as all problems were solved. And how thoughtful they are. I just remember next day CALLING that person to thank and he said ""koi nahi sir aap hamare liye intna sochte ho toh hamara bhi kuch farz banta hai. Koi bhi problem ho sidha mujhai call kjhiea"" Really respect for hyundai. Although I am now transferred to other state I remember them and Now I have exchanged my i10 with Verna suggested by him, even better. Regards Major K P Sinha."

author: pranshu gupta
comment_text: I got the car repaired under insurance. All fine. (VIN: MALCU41ULDM108334).   Then I got a call that car has no fuel from the service technician Yogender (9958211553). I said, ok, get 1-2 liters done. Now, I went to collect my car and was told that Rs. 500 worth of diesel has been bought from market in a can and filled in my car. When I enquired why 500 ( more than 9 liters), I was told that diesel car cant start in 1-2 liters of fuel and we took a call of 500 rs. I trusted and I was fine. I paid and when i went to collect the car. I realised that the car is in 'reserve sign'. There is limited fuel in the car and as per indicator not worth 9 liters.  So I called back the technician, who assured me that 500 rs was spent for fuel.  Since the car has a 43 liter fuel capacity and a reserve mark of 5-6 liters I was not convinced and called for the duty manager. The manager told me, we can take a can and a pipe, suck out diesel and thats it! When i objected to the vague explanatnation, I was told, it will take 4 hours, we will take out fuel tank and assure you. And everything was happening in a tone of mocking me for pointing out that there has been some misdeed.  I argued endlessly but what can a poor bloody customer with just one car do to a company which sells thousands in a month! So i came back with my teeth clenched and decided to write this email.  They showed me receipt of 500 rs for diesel bought, which has no validity since it does not have the car number and any such receipt can be procured from a pump (especially since the fuel station is next door to the service station).   I am not sure what your policies are, since you anyways sell so many cars and your dealers have the 'right' to loot the customers.   I have been looted and I need an answer!

comment_text: "We bought a 2nd hand kia (same as hyundai) back in 2006, it was 2 years old... It had extremely low mileage and was in perfect shape... We've had some other cars during the same time, but the only one what keeps looking as good as then is the kia, the only one that hasn't needed anything else than oil changes and tyres, has been the kia...It just drinks 5 liters of diesel per 100km, 125hp, air conditioning, power steering, power windows... not the fastest car ever but more than some of the extremely appreciated TDI's here... I know its not the same af the video, of course, but comparing cars at ""the same level"", this are extremely underrated cars for just no reason...Today, people buys a brand for what it ""means"", for the ""status"" it gives, just to show what they can buy... author: Kane K
comment_text: "just purchased a 2016 Hyundai i30 here in Australia. Our models come with more standard kit than the model you reviewed here. mine has parking sensors, reverse camera, touch screen multimedia centre, cruise control, and apple car play. only downside is there is no CD player. car is amazing, drives well; build quality is excellent. all this is standard on the ""active"" version (base model).  Australia is the ""biggest market"" for the i30 globally.   I looked at several other cars including the VW polo (great car, too small for me as I am 6ft 3). Toyota corolla (looked boring) and ford fiesta (too expensive). it was either the i30 or a Kia Cerato; as soon as I threatened to look at the Cerato, they matched the drive away price on the cerato for the i30. I am extremely happy with my choice, as the engine has a decent power output compared to the corolla or the polo. another big factor was the 5 year/unlimited km warranty.Â  No wonder Holden and ford struggle to sell the Cruze and fiesta respectively."

author: Doug N
comment_text: I bought this car back in 2013 and drove it 3 years and 80K miles. I had zero problems with it. I foolishly put new tires on the car a month before trading it and had the alignment checked. It was still in perfect alignment. Never had a car stay that true after all those miles. btw...I traded it in on a 2016 Elantra SE sedan. I must say the two cars, although same drive train, are different on the road. The GT definately had a sportier crisper feel whereas the sedan is softer and cushier over all. The sedan also is quiter and gets a tad better mpg. I miss the hatchback practicality of the GT but I like the looks of the sedan better. The GT was my first Hyundai and I must admit I'm sold. A Hyundai enthusiast.

author: John Benton
comment_text: I had a Hyundai I30 for three years, and I've just replaced it with a Hyundai IX20 because I needed more space. With the IX20 the 3-speed auto box soaks up lots of power and changes at too high a speed, so throttle response is almost non-existent. Economy is poor too, but otherwise the IX20 does all that's asked of it. (I just came back from 2 weeks' holiday,in a place about 180 miles of motorway from home. The car cruised at well above the speed limit (70 mph) and returned about 50 mpg. My previous car, an I30 diesel auto was just as fast, a bit quicker and did over 70 mpg, but it was a much smaller car. Will I have another Hyundai? You can bet on it!

author: Hector Rivera
comment_text: I have one for a year (august 28). The car is roomy even in the backseat (I'm 1.80 m) with good legroom (more than ford focus, toyota corolla ascent, mazda 3 neo), mine is the 1.6 gas and have enoughÂ power for a city car. Have electric folding mirrors, motorized tilting headlight (Almost standard on Europe, but not here in PanamÃ¡) wich you need to manually tilt in case you feel they're not bright enough, the front seats are very confortable, There are not cup holders in the back, but the center seat is more confortable than the ones with cup holders, I don't really know any problem with the AC, here in Panama is very hot, and the AC performs really good. The front pillar are thick and it may reduce visibility, thatÂ´s true. I bought the i30 over the focus because of the interior design that is simply far better than the focus, The fuel economy ir great. The exterior is really beautiful, a more complex design that turn heads. The handling is soft and the car is very quite. this is more like the elantra hatckback. May be you like the design may be not. May be you donÂ´t like Korean cars, but honestly, this car is amaizing for the tag price and I highly recomend the i30.

author: William Jones
comment_text: You guys really should have gotten the elantra sport as a comparison to the mazda 3. That would have been a more fair review even though the elantra sport has a bit more HP. Well, actually that shouldn't be an issue since the Mazda clearly had more HP and torque than the elantra you tested. I'm a mazda 3 owner and I love the car however I have test driven the Elantra sport and find that version to be equally enjoyable as my Mazda.  By the way I totally agree with you, I don't like the new design of the Elantra, the subtly and understated look of the previous model just looked better and the read made the newer model just look gaudy and cheap. I'm not sure how I feel about the new Mazda 3 design (I have the refreshed 2016). I think they should have went a bit more bold with the design and took more elements from the Kai design. I do like the back end better. I would say that has been the worst attribute to the mazda. They have these beautiful front ends and sides with a very pedestrian back end. It's akin to a women with big tits, a pretty face but no ass in the back. The Honda by contrast would be the women who's all ass but not much in terms of face or boobs. The elantra, at least the older model would have been the chick you normally wouldn't notice until you talk to her and once you do that's when you're pleasantly surprised. With the new model it looks like the unassuming chick in order to be noticed got botched plastic surgery.

author: Hoserfishing
comment_text: I owned a 2013 Hyundai Elantra 1.8L  at 98,000 kms I took it to the dealer before the warranty was to expire. It had a very slight tick at idle. They rebuilt the engine at zero dollars my cost. Explained why they rebuilt it and what was updated to prevent the same issue in future. It had a coating on the pistons and some fuel companies additives were reacting with the coating and causing issues. So yeah they are having issues but their elantra got 50 mpg Imperial gallons and was as smooth as butter to drive, shifted excellent, superb handling, comfortable, way nicer to drive than most vehicles on the road.  With their awesome warranty I think that I have a new engine and  it has the issues corrected that caused the problem. Customer service was amazing as well.  My parents test drove a brand new toyota and cut short their test drive as it was so noisy on the road you couldn't have a conversation. Said it was a piece of scrap to be that tinny sounding.  Would buy another new Hyundai/Kia in a second because of their warranty and commitment to their customers.

comment_text: I can second the anecdotal evidence on Hyundai's recent improvements in quality. A bit of info first: My mum lives in a suburban capital city and drives to work in an inland mountain town in Australia. The reasons for this involve a serious number of jobs being cut with the company she works for and she's been there for nealy 30 years; if she hangs onto her job she gets a big payout when they finally cut hers (the contract she signed in the 80s was hella sweet, and her union protects remaining perm. staff well.)   Sorry for the tangent, but that's why she commutes so far rather than leaving her current job.   Anyway, she drives a Kia, which is is pretty much a no-frills Hyundai. It has done 25000 km on it with no problems, and no issues during service. She's had it just shy of a year. When I was a kid (2002-ish,) Kia and Hyndai had a BAD rep after they released their sedans and 7-seater wagons, it took almost a decade to shake the bad reputation.

author: Chas Peking
comment_text: true story. In the 1980s I had amassed several 500-850cc Fiats with the intent of setting up a sugar beet or sugar cane import and distribution for the purpose of participating mechanically minded people who wanted to fuelling their own rigs. I had worked out the necessary measures of altering the carburators, etc. so this system and endeavor would most likely succeed. I forgot one thing. Fiat cars are junk. Fortunately I had to move overseas and the idea crumbled into an early grave. 13 years later, after dropping off a car at a Big Island resort area, I walked out to the highway to thumb a quick ride to Kona. After about 5-10 minutes, I heard the strangest mechanical noise I had ever heard from an automobile still able to drive on a highway came within earshot long before I could see it. I was anxious to learn the source of this multiple 12-11 teeth gear intermeshing and non-harmonic ignition firing pattern sound. It was the FIRST NEW resurrected Fiat 500 cruising from Kawaihae Harbor to Kona. I hoped the car made it. Folks, that car did not have even one hint of mechanical harmony to its name and I heard it a long way down the highway before I saw it. Imagine the sound of an engine with four pistons but only three cylinders wrapped up in a thick rug and you are getting close.

comment_text: So it's evidentially a metaphor for being trapped with car purchases. All the other floors, despite how they typically portray them as unenviable situations, they are all progressive in their actions. Unnecessary evils if you will.   The car however, is on the top floor of a starkly contrasted room, with absolutely no possibility of driving it, just the signifier, that instead of being outdoors and enjoying life, you are only observing it through a glass window.   Key lesson in life? You probably don't need a new car.

comment_text: Great job Soyfan. Initially, the headlights threw me for a loop, not your traditional placement. I'd be concerned about road debris with them being so low. However, as time went on they grew on me. They fit the vehicle and are consistent with the design language. I like the Telluride head lights but they seem a little small for the large grill. I'd go with the Palisade for two key reasons. 1) Their digital gauge cluster (on the higher trim) and 2) Their power folding third row seats. The Telluride doesn't offer those and I don't like the Telluride infotainment screen set up. I think the tablet on dash design is too common. Kudos to Hyundai for taking some design risks to separate themselves in this crowded segment.

author: kmg501
comment_text: The idea is trying to do too much which is why this is never going to market. If you needed an extreme ATV we already have many simpler designs available and the same is true for normal road vehicles. Also a vehicle like this one would make more sense with six legs instead of four if your objective is extreme ATV use. This vehicle could make sense IF many of the body parts could be fabricated by injection molding of an extremely durable and cost effective material.  Once the code has been developed thoroughly much of your work has been done, then it is just a materials cost issue and maintenance issue. In any event, don't look for this any time soon if ever. It's too niche and too extreme.

author: Mark Bader
comment_text: I test drove one of these, and I can say they're an awesome driving vehicle. However, only the deluxe version is available right now, and in CDN currency, after taxes and with no rebates available where I live, the e-Kona would cost $60,240. A regular Kona - the maxed out Ultimate AWD, leather interior, etc, only comes to $36,892. So, how much carbon emitting dirty stuff can I buy for the $23,000 difference? I'm thinking it's a lot. Aside from this, the Ultimate e-Kona is the only version worth considering (again, its also the only model available) given the range for the 64kWh battery of 415km is barely acceptable, in my opinion. I'm going to have to wait until battery production around the world ramps up and the price comes down, at which point I imagine a 700km range (with a sub 1-hour charge time) in an EV will be standard.

author: Dietmar Krauss-Varban
comment_text: This vehicle is just both tiny and super-expensive in the EV market. I leased my much larger (interior and cargo space) e-Golf for just $140/month, after combined state and federal discounts (note that that price has doubled, now - no thank you...). Most EV buyers don't care about range much beyond ~100 - 150 miles, because they know another car or a rental car or Uber or whatnot can fill the gaps, if needed (in three years, I never had to - except for our regular family commuter and second car for vacation trips).   *Manufacturers:*  long range just hurts handling, economy, and sales price. Just don't do it. Instead, focus on batteries that despite battery management don't lose 25% charge in as little as three years or 15,000 miles... basically eliminating EVs as a purchase (vs. lease) vehicle...

author: Francis Galiegue
comment_text: I disagree wrt interior space in the Niro compared to the Kona. The Niro is much more spacious and has a quite larger boot as well. Also, I think the central console layout of the Niro is better done.   Here in Europe the Niro is approximately â‚¬2k more than the Kona; but it would definitely be my choice. It's just a pity that you can't specify the higher trim level without a sun roof which I do not like or want.   There are two more things which I dislike with both:   * no app support! Well, there is, but in South Korea only. Come on, Hyundai/Kia... * you can't preheat/precool the car with the climate control if it's not plugged in! I can do that in my e-Golf... Which also has app support, by the way!

author: Hi Lot
comment_text: Guys, great reviews...on all the niceties of the vehicles features, etc. Like your take on these reviews. But what about the issues and engines problems of these 2.0 and 2.4 engines of Hyundai and Kia? Should we not discuss this, too? I would not buy a 2.0 or 2.4 vehicles from either of these engine from either of these brands.   The V6 engine is a safer bet with the Korean makes. Saying that, Hyundai and Kia are not up to the quality of the GM, Toyota or Honda engines. Just Google the engine issues on these brands for the 2.0 and 2.4. All sorts of web sites listing problems and comment and problems for current owners.  Issues galore.  Even Consumers Reports has an article on these engines and to avoid them. CR is more interesting in getting you to buy a vehicle and less likely to tell you of any problems.  They are catching fire and are also seizing up due to poor manufacturing defects.   And all the recalls on these engines. No turbo engine or regular 4 banger from Hyundai or Kai in my future.   I am in the process of looking for an SUV or this size.

author: George Marx
comment_text: I have been driving a 2011 Santa Fe since new, nearly 90k on it now. Still runs and drives great, but I crave the latest Infotainery, as well as the accident-avoidance systems. So, I've driven the '19 Santa Fe, and it is pretty great - as you both concluded. It might be my next vehicle. But hold on a tick. In the last eight years, the Santa Fe is quite a bit bigger, and it now has a kid brother - the Tucson. And the '19 Tucson is almost exactly the same size and weight as my '11 Santa Fe. I've driven it as well, and may opt to save the $2-3000, and gain a bit better mileage (250 lbs lighter), and better handling. What do the Straight Pipes Guys think? Going to drive the Tucson soon?  I've got to agree with you, Yuri - I hate Auto Climate because I crave the ability to have a bit of outside air in the cabin, with the windows down! Is this possible in the Hyundais, or the Mazda CX-5, or the Subaru Forester?

author: Janne Oksanen
comment_text: "Nice review & video again! I owned a Mk2 Santa Fe for some time, tested the Mk3 once but was disappointed by few things: less ground clearance, less space and even the driver's sitting position was lower, more hatchback-like. My Mk2 felt far more sure-footed in slush than the Mk3, and the almost 200 horses in newer diesel engine were either really old or just tired, because the engine felt about as sluggish as the puny 155hp diesel in my Mk2... Kind of sucks this Mk4 is yet again another step towards street driving. I also hate how Hyundai cloned Audi/BMW style dashboard design. On top of that, there's the price, which isn't that competitive here in FIN anymore. And, having owned several ""bad reputation"" cars before, like CitroÃ«ns, Peugeot, Renault and Korean Chevrolet, I have to say I'd MUCH rather replace one or two electrical components (maybe 50 to 100eur each) in them per year, than do a complete engine & turbocharger swap (over 7000eur with refurbished parts) to a ""reliable"" Hyundai..."

author: Peter Lau
comment_text: Thanks for the review on the Santa Fe. It looks to be an improvement on the superseded model and should be quite competitive in it's class. Answering your question, when we were purchasing a new car a few months ago we went the MPV route instead of getting a SUV - I have no need to drag around an AWD system or big wheels, and the high ride height meant that the SUVS I test drove didn't have good ride comfort.

author: Huw Williams
comment_text: This could be a contender for people who have a Honda CR-V diesel automatic [like I have] and want to change it for a similar car, but Honda now only sell petrol with a damn IVT automatic. However if it comes in at just under the price of a mid spec Volvo XC60 D4 auto, I'd go for the Volvo [I also have an XC90]. The Hyundai has an excellent reliability reputation and superb warranty and, in my case a dealer within 30kms [Volvo is only 5kms away though]. It would be way up on my shortlist until LR get the Discovery Sport engine sorted, then I could compare the Discovery Sport 9 speed automatic with the Hyundai 8 speed, as it happens at the very same dealership in my case. They sell both.

comment_text: Kia & Hyundai cheap Korean cars. Had one, 2013 Rio EX that developed an engine knock and later a total engine failure, lucky it never caught fire but I had to pay $1700 to get a new motor short block installed, it just happened to fail me at 100685 miles on the odometer when it failed on me. I will never buy a Korean car again. I rather by 10 15 year old Mercedes S class, BMW 7 series, Audi A8 or S8. Than a sensible low class low quality automobile. for the price I paid for my 2013 Kia Rio EX of $18400 I could have bought any of the above prestigious brands and drive with class and style. I really regret buying the Kia. So if you are thinking about getting a Kia, don't do it. Get a used, 10 to 15 year old Mercedes, BMW, or Audi, sure they are expensive to maintain but they have class style and safety that Kia can't never match period, plus they will bring up your self esteem unlike Kia and Hyundai with no self esteem. Or if you just want a super reliable daily driver buy a used Toyota, Honda, Mazda, or Subaru, as these cars do have bulletproof reliability they are also an excellent buy over any Kia or Hyundai period. Sorry if you are a Kia or Hyundai fan boy or girl but this are the facts period!!

I figured the problem out and replaced the sensor but the company designed it knowing the oil sensor will go out of eventually so they designed it to were the oil will funnel down between the transmission and the engine right on top of the exhaust when it does, very badd design flaw!!!!! comment_text: Hyundai is a Crooked company. I bought a 2013 Elantra in 2012. A few months after getting it, the car went into manual mode @ 85 mph, from 6th to 2nd gear. Did that 4 times. Motor started knocking. Took it the dealership, they said it was a standard tick. Went to trade it in that day, found out there were 3 contracts on that car. 1 signed the one I had, the dealership forged the other 2. None of the contracts matched. I told hyundai to come get the car. I tried to turn that car into 3 different hyundai dealers and all 3 threatened me with police action. Beought the forgery to the attention of the NC State police & the DA of Greenville NC. Neither office would press charges for forgery. A year later hyundai Finally came & got the car. Now im fighting hyundai over the repo on my credit. Hyundai SUCKS !!! They build garbage.

author: ponymoonshadow
comment_text: Here is what I like better about the 2019 over the 2018... the rear trunk spoiler, the license plate placement and the infotainment drive mode graphics.... that's it, nothing more. I do not like the harsh knife edge angular styling of the 2019, and I HATE the wheels! Here's a little thing you complained about, no cover for the storage where the power plugs are. Guess what, the 2018 has a very nice cover.  The 2019 may be a comfortable sporty fun drive, but that is no different from the 2018. Same powertrain, same underpinnings, handling and performance. The difference between the two is the styling, and I LOVE the 2018 look! is much better styling than the 2019, which I feel will become dated very quickly. I'm glad I bought my sport (fully loaded in the beautiful Electric Blue with 7sp DCT) before the 2019 styling change! If I had to chose between my old 2013 Elantra Coupe (which I traded in on my 2018 Sport), and the 2019 Sport, I would have kept my Coupe with only 14k miles on it. If I dont like the styling of a car, I wont buy a car no matter how well it performs. The 2018 has everything I wanted. Good looks (which in my opinion the 2019 lacks), comfort, and the bonus of wonderful fun to drive performance and handling which my 2013 lacked. Thanks for the great review, but I'm still glad I bought my 2018 instead of the 2019.
